  "prompt": "Why am I allergic to dogs and not to cats?",
  "response": "Allergies to pets are typically caused by proteins found in their skin cells, urine, saliva, and other bodily secretions. The reason you may be allergic to dogs and not to cats can depend on a few factors:\n\n1. **Different Proteins**: Different animals produce distinct allergenic proteins. In dogs, the primary allergens are often found in their saliva (especially when they groom themselves) and skin. Cats have their own specific proteins (notably Fel d 1) that can also trigger allergies. If your immune system reacts only to the proteins found in dogs, you may not have a reaction to those found in cats.\n\n2. **Exposure**: Your level of exposure to dogs compared to cats can also affect your sensitivity. If you have had more prolonged or closer contact with dogs, it's possible that your immune system has developed a sensitivity to their allergens.\n\n3. **Genetic Factors**: Allergies can have a genetic component. Your individual genetic makeup influences how your immune system reacts to different allergens, which is why some people are allergic to certain animals and not others.\n\n4. **Environmental Factors**: Certain environmental factors can also influence allergies. The presence of dust, pollen, and other allergens in your environment can exacerbate your reaction to specific animals.\n\n5. **Immune System Variability**: Everyone's immune system is unique, leading to individual variations in allergic responses. Some people may react strongly to certain proteins and not to others.\n\nIf your allergies are bothersome, consider consulting an allergist for specific testing and management strategies.",
